[1] Cholera - Zimbabwe
Date: Mon 23 Mar 2015
Source: Xinhua News Agency [edited]
http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2015-03/23/c_134090605.htm


Zimbabwe's capital Harare, where an Ebola outbreak killed more than 4000 people in 2008, remains on high alert in March 2015 following 14 reported cases of cholera in the country since late February 2015. The city has not recorded any cases of the disease, but conditions for an outbreak remain favorable, however, with the council not being able to provide enough potable water, while fruit and vegetable vendors as well as those selling pre-cooked food are literally littering the streets.

Cholera is mainly transmitted through contaminated water and food and is closely linked to inadequate environmental management, including poor refuse collection, which is also common in the city. The situation is made ominous due to the fact that 434 cases of watery diarrhea were reported in the city in the 2nd week of March 2015, compared to the 361 reported in the previous week.

Director of health services Prosper Chonzi told journalists that there had been no confirmed cases of cholera in the city. "All cases of diarrhea are being sent for further investigations and we are happy that since the beginning of the outbreak, there has not been any single case of cholera recorded in Harare," Chonzi said. Most of the cholera cases have been reported in Beitbridge, on the border with South Africa, and Mashonaland East province along the border with Mozambique.

The government recently dispatched health teams to Mudzi District in the province following 3 reported cholera cases there, with Health and Child Care Minister David Parirenyatwa saying that there was need for cooperation between Zimbabwe and Mozambique. Mozambique has been identified as the source of the current cholera cases which have spread to neighboring Malawi and Zimbabwe.

According to the United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs, as of 13 Mar 2015 Mozambique had recorded 5894 cases and 47 deaths since 25 Dec 2014, Malawi 88 cases and 2 deaths since 13 Feb 2015, and Zimbabwe 14 cases and no deaths since late February 2015.

Zimbabwe recorded Africa's worst cholera outbreak in decades between 2008 and 2010 when more than 4200 people died from about 100 000 reported cases following the virtual collapse of the public health system. The outbreak spread to neighboring countries, especially South Africa and Botswana, as people travelled there to seek medical assistance.

[Byline: Tichaona Chifamba]

