[2] Cholera - Ghana (Greater Accra Region)
Date: Sun 22 Mar 2015
Source: GhanaWeb [edited]
http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/artikel.php?ID=351417


In spite of the fact that many health facilities in the Greater Accra Region recorded high numbers of cholera cases in 2014, TV3's Catherine Frempong reports that holding centres which were to be constructed to arrest a possible outbreak in subsequent years were yet to be completed. This means pressure on health facilities could worsen in 2015, as nearly a hundred cases have been recorded in the Greater Accra Region alone. The construction of the holding centres which started during last year's [2014] outbreak have mostly stalled, while others have broken down. In 2014, the Greater Accra Region alone saw over 20 000 cholera cases, with over 2000 deaths.

"We did not declare the epidemic over so we didn't get to zero before we ended 2014. We were still recording cases even in December 2014. But it had reduced drastically compared to what we were recording in the middle of the year when we had the rains" that's according to Greater Accra Regional Health Director Dr Linda Van-Otoo. The outbreak last year [2014] exposed the unpreparedness of most health facilities as majority of them had no cholera holding bays, whiles those which had were overwhelmed by inadequate space.

The Ridge Hospital OPD [outpatient department] at Adabrabraka as of 18 Mar 2015, had 90 cases. The cholera bay with cholera cots, which hosted patients 2014, is no longer reliable. Cases are now treated at the OPD. "The bed that they lie on has a hole in it and a bucket is put under the hole; so when the diarrhea comes they just come as if they've turned on the tap. So sitting or even lying on a mattress where there is no hole will not be good. So those are the areas we also need improvement in."

LEKMA Hospital, recorded 1427 cases with 18 deaths in 2014, using a makeshift ward, a cholera bay which started after the outbreak has stalled; and already 2 cases have been reported. "If we run into the epidemic that we had last year, it will be a big challenge for us if that isolation center is not completed as soon as possible; a health official at LEKMA cautioned.

The Greater Accra Regional Health Director appealed to individuals and corporate organizations to assist the health facilities to complete the cholera isolation centers. Dr Linda Van-Otoo confirmed that the region alone has recorded 100 cases as of 18 Mar 2015, and thus asked residents to observe good hygienic practices to prevent the disease.

