[4] Cholera - Kenya (Bomet County)
Date: Tue 17 Mar 2015
Source: AllAfrica, The Star [edited]
http://allafrica.com/stories/201503171111.html


Hotels in Bomet town have been closed following a cholera outbreak. 2 people have died and 33 others admitted in hospital. The cases were reported in Chepalungu and Bomet on Fri 13 Mar 2015

Health executive Stanley Kiplangat attributed the outbreak to water shortages in the county. He said residents fetch untreated water from Nyangores River for use in hotels, restaurants and at home. Kiplangat addressed the press in Bomet town yesterday. He said many hotel owners buy water, whose source is unknown, from boda boda [bicycle or motorcycle taxis] operators and water bowsers [tankers]. Water levels at Nyangores River have gone down because of drought.

Some residents have accused the county government of not setting up effective measures to address the outbreak. They said one hotel was exempted from closure. Residents said the hotel owner uses water from Nyangores River. Other hotel owners said he is well connected to powerful county officials.

"The county government has failed terribly. This is the hotel that discharges its raw sewer to this main river but we are surprised it has been left out," a businessman told the Star in Bomet town. "It is very wrong and we are contemplating challenging this or taking some stern action."

